04247nam a22007215i 9780813594514DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135945147 a10.36019/97808135945142doi  a(DE-B1597)529833  a(OCoLC)1125186786  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN6728.W6 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a741.5/9732231 aBerlatsky, Noah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWonder Woman :bBondage and Feminism in the Marston/Peter Comics, 1941-1948 /cNoah Berlatsky. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2017] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b32 color illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComics Culture00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- tChapter One. The Pink Bondage Goo of Feminism -- tChapter Two. Castration in Paradise -- tChapter Three. Candy You Can Eat -- tConclusion. A Future without Wonder Woman -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWilliam Marston was an unusual man—a psychologist, a soft-porn pulp novelist, more than a bit of a carny, and the (self-declared) inventor of the lie detector. He was also the creator of Wonder Woman, the comic that he used to express two of his greatest passions: feminism and women in bondage. Comics expert Noah Berlatsky takes us on a wild ride through the Wonder Woman comics of the 1940s, vividly illustrating how Marston’s many quirks and contradictions, along with the odd disproportionate composition created by illustrator Harry Peter, produced a comic that was radically ahead of its time in terms of its bold presentation of female power and sexuality. Himself a committed polyamorist, Marston created a universe that was friendly to queer sexualities and lifestyles, from kink to lesbianism to cross-dressing. Written with a deep affection for the fantastically pulpy elements of the early Wonder Woman comics, from invisible jets to giant multi-lunged space kangaroos, the book also reveals how the comic addressed serious, even taboo issues like rape and incest. Wonder Woman: Bondage and Feminism in the Marston/Peter Comics 1941-1948 reveals how illustrator and writer came together to create a unique, visionary work of art, filled with bizarre ambition, revolutionary fervor, and love, far different from the action hero symbol of the feminist movement many of us recall from television.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBondage (Sexual behavior) in literature. 0aComic books, strips, etczUnited States. 0aFeminism in literature. 0aWomen in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081359451440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813594514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813594514.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK